Class XlList

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • java.util.ArrayList<XlBean>
          • org.xlbean.XlList
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<XlBean>, java.util.Collection<XlBean>, java.util.List<XlBean>, java.util.RandomAccess

    public class XlList
extends java.util.ArrayList<XlBean>
    Inherits ArrayList with additional utility methods suitable for common data structure of excel.

    All the tables defined in excel is represented as XlList of XlBean instances.

      • aggregate

        public XlList aggregate(java.lang.String childListName,
                        java.lang.String... parentKeys)
        Convert a denormalized list of one to many relation objects into parent object with list of children objects.

        Suppose you have a table of companies and employees in a excel sheet. In each row of the table, there are a name of an employee and a name of a company which the employee belongs to. When this table is loaded by XlBean, you will get an instance of XlList filled with multiple instances of XlBean as elements, and each of the XlBean instance has name of an employeeName and a companyName.

        Now you want to have a list of companies which has list of employees inside each instance of company. This can be done by calling this method with "employees" as childListName and ["companyName"] as parentKeys.

        Parameters:
        childListName -
        parentKeys -
        Returns:

      • find

        public XlBean find(java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> conditionMap)
        Returns the first element matches conditionMap.

        All the keys and values in the conditionMap is used to check if elements in this list matches with it.

        The matching starts from index 0 to the end of this list one by one until matched element. If there is no element to be matched, then it returns null.

        Parameters:

        Returns:
